WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   STOCK PRICES SURGED as the earnings worries that jolted
the market Friday vanished. The Dow Jones Industrial Average
soared 49.57 points to 2870.49, a record close. The S&amp;P 500
index also set a new high, its first since October. Bond
prices rose steadily, while the dollar was mixed.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Revlon accepted new terms on a pending $1.8 billion bank
loan amid regulatory pressure on banks to limit lending to
highly leveraged concerns.
   ---
   Xerox faces new write-offs at its Crum &amp; Forster insurance
unit that could approach $400 million, insurance-industry
executives and analysts say.
   ---
   Ford told dealers it may nearly double incentives on 1990
autos after next year's models go on sale in October. The
disclosure may hurt the auto maker's sales this summer.
   ---
   Harcourt named former Energy Secretary John Herrington as
chairman, succeeding William Jovanovich, whose son will
follow him as head of the publisher's executive committee.
   ---
   UAL's unions are talking to Chrysler Vice Chairman Gerald
Greenwald about taking the top job at United Airlines if an
employee buy-out succeeds, sources said.
   ---
   Federal Express overcame an obstacle to efficiency as it
won clearance to merge its pilot seniority list with that of
Tiger International, which Federal acquired last year.
   ---
   Westinghouse is expected to name Paul Lego chairman and
chief executive in a move that could put the company on a
growth course.
   ---
   Equimark's Judith Fellheimer resigned her top management
position, ending the bank holding company's husband-wife
management team.
   ---
   Massachusetts may adopt a 5% sales tax on professional
services that are largely untaxed by states.
   ---
   Drexel's brokerage unit filed for Chapter 11
bankruptcy-law protection along with 14 Drexel subsidiaries.
   ---
   William Farley's bondholders may seek to wrest from him
voting control of West Point-Pepperell. But the creditors may
try to avoid a forced liquidation of the firm because of a
perception that Farley overpaid for it.
   ---
   The securities industry won a case in Supreme Court. The
justices let stand a lower court's finding that Massachusetts
can't stop brokerage firms from requiring customers to sign
arbitration agreements.
   ---
   Source Perrier agreed to sell most of its soft-drink
business to Cadbury Schweppes for $211 million.
   ---
   Chase Manhattan is opening 10 offices nationwide to offer
investment advice to well-off people who aren't wealthy
enough to qualify for Chase's "private banking" department.
   ---
   Concern about Macy's creditworthiness led an insurer to
tighten its policy for firms with links to Macy.
   ---
   Tyco Laboratories agreed to buy the operating assets of an
Australian maker of fire-protection gear for about $600
million in cash and stock.
   ---
   DHL International is selling minority stakes to Lufthansa,
Japan Air and a Japanese trading company.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 137,410,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2870.49, up 49.57; transportation 1162.52, up 9.78; utilities
